    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d85a4089_5b5a5dc2",
        "filename": "client/annotation.h",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 88,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-10-13T18:26:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The voidy interface is a typehole. I’d rather have something a little better be exposed to users.\n\nPerhaps Annotation can be templated, where template \u003ctypename ValueType\u003e class Annotation would have a const ValueType* const value_ptr_ field.\n\nIn that world, the sizes of many annotations could be inferred directly as sizeof(typename ValueType). That’d even work for something like “static Annotation\u003cchar[PAGE_SIZE]\u003e g_buffer_annotation \u003d {…};”. Of course, if you want something external to push in explicit sizing rather than having Annotation (or a specialization) know about NUL-termination, you’d still want to hang on to a SetSize() kind of thing. But even then, it’d give SetSize() the ability to check against the known maximum buffer size. That’d be nice too.\n\nIf you’d like, you can take this a little further still, and move storage into the Annotation itself (rather than having it point to external data). That’d make Annotation even easier to use.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 88,
        "startChar": 53,
        "endLine": 88,
        "endChar": 74
      },
      "revId": "8ea2b5e2f1f00ab7062a34d722909c4581c7dd93",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8efaa4c1_90a9bd06",
        "filename": "client/annotation.h",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 88,
      "author": {
        "id": 1144624
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-10-13T22:33:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e The voidy interface is a typehole. I’d rather have something a little better be exposed to users.\n\u003e \n\u003e Perhaps Annotation can be templated, where template \u003ctypename ValueType\u003e class Annotation would have a const ValueType* const value_ptr_ field.\n\u003e \n\u003e In that world, the sizes of many annotations could be inferred directly as sizeof(typename ValueType). That’d even work for something like “static Annotation\u003cchar[PAGE_SIZE]\u003e g_buffer_annotation \u003d {…};”. Of course, if you want something external to push in explicit sizing rather than having Annotation (or a specialization) know about NUL-termination, you’d still want to hang on to a SetSize() kind of thing. But even then, it’d give SetSize() the ability to check against the known maximum buffer size. That’d be nice too.\n\nI originally wanted to go down the the templatized route, but that breaks down when you need to work with the link_node_ and AnnotationList where there is not a homogeneous type.\n\nRe: SetSize(): I still want to be able to set the value size externally for e.g. a future StackTrace annotation type, where we may store space for 32 pointers but only use 12.\n\n\u003e If you’d like, you can take this a little further still, and move storage into the Annotation itself (rather than having it point to external data). That’d make Annotation even easier to use.\n\nIt\u0027s deliberate to be able to point to external storage. I think most users will not be using Annotation directly, but rather one of its Type helper subclasses.",
      "parentUuid": "d85a4089_5b5a5dc2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 88,
        "startChar": 53,
        "endLine": 88,
        "endChar": 74
      },
      "revId": "8ea2b5e2f1f00ab7062a34d722909c4581c7dd93",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
